# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-rights-without-liberation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was the son of a surgeon and was born at Waiblingen in 1677.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] He studied theology at Württemberg but also took interest in anatomy and natural science.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen became a pastor and advocate of pietism in Leonberg.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was influenced by the writings of Philipp Spener.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen argued for a compassionate treatment of the animals from a Christian theological framework.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] In 1711, Weigen authored *De Jure Hominis in Creaturas*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] It has been described as "the first work ever to deal with the topic of animal rights as a general theme." The book became known in Denmark and inspired Laurids Smith.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen moved to Wahlheim, where he died in 1727.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The book is based upon Cochrane's doctoral thesis, which was completed at the London School of Economics, and builds upon subjects he had discussed in previous publications, including his first book.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] It was published by Columbia University Press as the second book in their series Critical Perspectives on Animals, edited by Gary Francione and Gary Steiner.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Critics from a variety of backgrounds responded positively to the book, focussing on how Cochrane had found a middle ground between traditional animal rights philosophy and utilitarianism.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] In addition to presenting ideas used in the book at meetings of the Political Theory Group at LSE, Cochrane published an article entitled "Animal interests and animal experiments: An interest-based approach" in the journal *Res Publica* in 2006.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] This article won the journal's second annual Postgraduate Essay Prize, and formed the basis of the third chapter of *Animal Rights Without Liberation*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane continued to work on questions of animal rights after the completion of his doctorate, publishing articles on the subject in *Utilitas* and *Political Studies* in 2009, the latter of which provoked responses from Garner in 2011 and the philosopher John Hadley in 2013.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane published his first book, *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*, through Palgrave Macmillan in 2010, after having moved to the Department of Politics at Sheffield University.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane's "interest-based rights approach" is the method utilised in the book to examine various ways in which animals are used by humans.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Rights set limits on what can be done, even in the pursuit of aggregative well-being.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The animal rights outlined by philosopher Tom Regan are based on the "inherent value" of individual animals *(see intrinsic value)*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] For Cochrane and other critics, this basis can seem "mysterious".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane draws out several aspects of this account, which serves as the basis of the analysis in *Animal Rights Without Liberation*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] First, interests must be "*sufficient* to give grounds for holding another to be under a duty".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Judging this entails considering the strength of an interest as well as "all other considerations"; so, for example, while individuals may have a very strong interest in free expression, but, "all things considered", this need not protect slander.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The greater interest of the victim of slander can outweigh the interest in free expression, and so context is important.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] This is the difference between *prima facie* rights and concrete rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The former exist on an abstract level outside of particular circumstances.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] *Prima facie* rights can translate into concrete rights when considered in particular situations but do not always, as the free expression example illustrates.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The account is for moral rights, and Cochrane's normative claims are intended to form part of a "democratic underlaboring", informing and persuading political communities.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The strength of an interest is determined by a consideration of the value of something to an individual (though this is not understood purely subjectively) and the relationship between the individual at this time and the individual when he or she has the interest satisfied *(see personal identity)*.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane argues that those beings who lack personhood, including many nonhuman animals and some humans, do not have an interest in liberty or not being used by others, and so have no *prima facie* right to freedom.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] They do, however, possess significant interests in not being made to suffer and in not being killed, and so have a *prima facie* right not to be made to suffer and a *prima facie* right not to be killed.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] At this point, Cochrane has completed the first two steps introducing his interest-based rights approach; the third is outlining the approach itself as the appropriate means of understanding obligations to animals in political communities.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Utilitarianism, as advocated by Peter Singer, is rejected because of its failure to take individuals seriously enough; Cochrane desires an account which takes well-being seriously but is not purely aggregative.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] This, he suggests, is one based on interest rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] After explicating the details of his interest-based rights approach, Cochrane defends it against the charge that it would result in an unworkably large number of rights, and that rights approaches are too rationalistic.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Having outlined his methodological approach, Cochrane goes on to apply his theory to a number of ways that animals are used by society.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane concludes that animals have a concrete right to not be subjected to painful experiments.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] If deadly experimentation on nonhuman non-persons is permitted, then consistency demands that it also be permitted on human non-persons, such as babies or individuals with certain cognitive disabilities.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Like most others, Cochrane is unwilling to allow this possibility, and so claims that animals have a right not to be used in deadly experiments.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] However, he argues that animals have neither an interest in negative or positive freedom, and, like animals, human non-persons also lack this interest; therefore, neither have a *prima facie* right not to be used, provided said use respects the rights they do possess.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The second considered application is animal agriculture.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane argues that animals possess concrete rights not to be made to suffer or be killed while being raised for food.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The book argues that factory farming inflicts suffering upon the animals used, and this suffering outweighs the cost to humans of not using the method.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Killing animals for their flesh is also challenged, and objections that this infringes on human liberty, that many humans would lose their jobs and that flesh-consumption is necessary for human health are all considered and rejected.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Milk and egg production may be permissible under certain circumstances, provided animals are not killed or made to suffer, and, equally, animal corpses could be used provided that the animals have died naturally.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Second, Cochrane considers the fact that some animals are killed by nonhuman predators.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] He rejects Regan's claim that intervention is not required when killers are not moral agents and the consequentialist claim that interference will do more harm than good, instead suggesting that nonhuman predators need to kill to survive, but humans do not.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Third, he considers the fact that animals are killed in the harvesting process.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] These animals, he suggests, are killed for human survival, but as fewer are killed than would be killed were humans eating meat, they do not possess a concrete right to life.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Despite this, political communities must take steps to ensure that fewer animals are killed in harvest.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] After looking at agriculture, Cochrane considers the relationship between animals and genetic engineering.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The question of whether an animal has a right not to be genetically engineered, he suggests, makes no sense, as live animals are not engineered, and embryos have no interests, so cannot have rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane finds none of these arguments reason to abandon the principle.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane considers whether animals may *ever* have a right not to have been engineered.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] He argues that animals have a right not to be engineered such that they have lives not worth living.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] However, Cochrane argues that he is not advocating perfectionism, as he is concerned not with equal capacities between members of a species, but equal opportunities for well-being.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Finally, Cochrane considers the possibility of engineering nonsentient, non-conscious livestock, arguing that, ordinarily, there is no wrong in engineering nonconscious entities.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Chapter six addresses the use of animals in entertainment.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane does not oppose the practice of pet-keeping, and accepts that humans do have an interest in being able to keep pets, but that this interest is not so strong that it can be satisfied at any cost.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] He argues that pet-keeping should be regulated far more than it is, perhaps through the need for a license, the granting of which would be dependent on individuals proving their ability to care for the animal's well-being.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane is open to euthanizing pets, but only in cases when medical care could not give them a chance at further good experiences.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] In these cases, providing medical care would be necessary (pet insurance could be a requirement for a license).
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Neutering pets is argued to be neither a violation of their rights nor a requirement, but anyone who does not have their pets neutered would be required to ensure the wellbeing of any offspring.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The same requirements as were established in the chapter on genetic engineering are applied to animal breeding, and Cochrane accepts that this may lead to the extinction of certain breeds.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Concerning zoos and circuses, Cochrane argues that animals do not possess a right not to be kept or displayed, but they do possess a right not to be made to suffer.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] This imposes limitations on the kinds of animals which can be kept (for instance, large animals could not realistically be kept by traveling circuses), the conditions in which they are kept, and the nature of their performances.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Hunting, cockfighting, dogfighting, bear baiting and bullfighting are condemned, as is, after some consideration, fishing.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] In chapter seven, Cochrane approaches issues relating to animals and the environment.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane considers, but rejects, the land ethic of Aldo Leopold as a basis for the moral status of the environment, but instead defends the environment on welfare grounds.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Though he rejects the notion that wild animals might own the land on which they live, Cochrane concludes that we have strict environmental obligations due to the rights and interests of sentient animals.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Concerning endangered species, Cochrane rejects the notion of "superkilling" (that a special wrong is involved in wiping out a species) and the idea of "compensatory justice" (that more is owed to members of endangered species as a form of compensation).
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Instead, Cochrane argues that unconscious species may have contingent value, and members of rare conscious species may have a stronger right to life due to the interests of humans who will want to see them and the interests of other animals in their ecosystems.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane then argues that animals possess a concrete right not to be killed in order to preserve a favoured ecosystem, whether because of overpopulation of the species or because species are nonnative.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] However, control by contraception is argued to be acceptable.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] In the final chapter on the application of the interest-based rights approach, Cochrane analyses the use of animals in cultural practices, considering the importance of culture, religion and a concern about hypocrisy.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane first looks at the possibility that humans have an interest in culture which outweighs certain interests of animals.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] He argues that it cannot be the case that culture can *always* outweigh other rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] He then argues the human interest culture cannot outweigh animal interests in not suffering, using jallikattu as his example, or outweigh animal interests in not being killed, even if this entails the destruction of cultures "defined entirely by the grave harm [they cause] to animals".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The human interest in freedom of religion, Cochrane claims, will usually not require the violation of animal interests, but cites Santeria as a possible exception to this.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane argues against the possibility that freedom of religion is a special interest and should always merit priority, and the idea that equal opportunity should entail religious freedom to harm animals.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Finally, Cochrane considers hypocrisy; given that animals are harmed in many practices, there may be a problem in disallowing certain religious practices.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] However, this does not make the religious practices more permissible, and seems to presuppose that these other practices will not themselves face censure.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The aim of *Animal Rights Without Liberation* was to "decouple animal rights and animal liberation".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane claims that not only is an alternative to the Regan/Singer dichotomy possible, but it is preferable.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] He argues that, though his theory would allow the use and ownership of animals in certain circumstances, the theory would nonetheless have "incredibly radical" consequences if applied.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The book has aimed to persuade people of the importance of animal rights, and thus serve as "democratic underlabouring".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] This democratic underlabouring, Cochrane claims, is essential for the legitimacy of animal rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Relatedly, Cochrane firmly rejects violent interventions on behalf of animals as counterproductive, immoral and illegitimate.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] represented a middle ground between animal rights approaches (as advocated by Tom Regan)...
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] ...and animal welfare approaches (as advocated by Peter Singer).
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] However, for Hadley, there is a fundamental tension in Cochrane's theory, as there is in most animal rights literature.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] In denying that animals possess the psychological capacities to value freedom, Cochrane undermines the challenge to orthodox rights theory that it is not only persons who should possess rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] For Hadley, "only theories that have no truck with commonsense intuitions at all, like Bentham's, are really in a position to place humans and animals on a genuinely equal moral plain.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Clifton suggested that Cochrane's thought is actually closer to Regan's.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Boisseau, though, suggested that, given that Cochrane allows some use of animals in entertainment and genetic engineering, the arguments of *Animal Rights Without Liberation* may come across as "radically permissive" when compared with those of other animal rights positions.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The permissibility of some forms of animal experimentation under Cochrane's account "may shock" supporters of approaches based upon Regan's philosophy.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Ebert concluded that "the great accomplishment of Cochrane's book is to show that there is a coherent, intuitively plausible, and useful notion of animal rights that is firmly rooted in the tangible and avoids the unattractive absolutism of Regan-style rights views".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Meijer felt that the book is strong on the application of Cochrane's account, but she expressed concern about Cochrane's rejection of liberty rights for animals, which, she noted, most approaches to animal rights allow.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane's deploys, she noted, a narrow account of animal agency; "it is", she argued, "problematic to view humans as autonomous agents and other animals as nonautonomous others".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane's view of animals as non-autonomous, she argued, is emphasised by the absence of an account of relationships and communication between humans and animals.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] If we believe that human nonpersons have a right not to be treated in such a degrading manner, then so do nonhuman animal nonpersons." Boisseau, too, found the aspect of Cochrane's thought dealing with "people with mental disabilities" to be "objectionable".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Clifton approvingly quoted the arguments in *Animal Rights Without Liberation* concerning animals killed in crop harvest, and observed that, other than a hypothetical openness towards ethically produced eggs and dairy, Cochrane's arguments would seem to favour veganism over vegetarianism.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The book was summarised in *Internet Bookwatch* as "[p]ragmatic, insightful, rational, iconoclastic, informed and informative".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Philosophers Peter Singer and Paula Casal praised work for exposing a false dichotomy of animal rights versus animal welfare, both seeing the work as an important contribution to the literature for this reason.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] In a quote used by Columbia University Press, Garner praised *Animal Rights Without Liberation* for being the first sustained attempt to use an interest-based theory of rights for animals, and the first to use such a theory to challenge animals' right to liberty.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] In his 2013 *A Theory of Justice for Animals*, Garner challenges Cochrane on his use of the argument from marginal cases.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] If animals are assumed to have an equal interest in life as typical humans because marginal humans are, then one could also assume animals to have an equal interest in liberty, because of the assumption of marginal humans' interest in liberty.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane, however, denies that marginal humans are assumed to have a strong interest in liberty.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The first part of the argument, Garner observes, assumes that marginal humans are considered to have an equal interest in (or an equal right to) life; this is a claim which Garner challenges, reaching what he considers a more nuanced position than Cochrane's.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Nonetheless, the ideal theory which Garner endorses—the enhanced sentience position—is close to Cochrane's interest-based rights position.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Garner himself identifies differences between his thought and Cochrane's in their respective use of the argument from marginal cases and the fact that Garner offers a nonideal theory, while Cochrane does not.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Garner also questions the extent to which Cochrane is right that his reliance on interest rights is new, suggesting that Feinberg, James Rachels and Steve Sapontzis all used the language of interest rights.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Garner adds that "what Cochrane does, unlike Sapontzis, is to draw what I think are the correct conclusions from the adoption of an interest-based theory of animal rights".
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Garner has also criticised Cochrane's rejection of liberty rights for animals; others to challenge this include Hadley and the philosophers Andreas T.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Schmidt, Valéry Giroux, and Jason Wyckoff.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane has developed his account in subsequent work, tying his work to cosmopolitan theory in a 2013 paper and developing an account of labour rights for animals in a 2016 paper.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] As of 2016, Cochrane is working on a book on the topic of animal rights and global justice, covering questions of cross-border obligations to nonhuman animals and the idea of international politics taking the rights of all sentient beings seriously.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] The book is intended for 2017 or 2018 release.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] A number of subsequent thinkers have deployed interest-based rights for animals, drawing upon Cochrane's work.
[src:animal-rights-without-liberation/animal-rights-without-liberation] Cochrane's work, especially *Animal Rights Without Liberation*, has been repeatedly identified as central to and paradigmatic of this literature.
